# OptiFuel Flowchart Guidance

Use this rule for workflow diagrams and React Flow implementations.

## Diagram Styling

- Match OptiFuel design language: cream canvas `#eeefe9`, flat white nodes, olive text, hairline borders.
- Typography: IBM Plex Sans Variable.
- Node surfaces: `#ffffff` with `1px` border `#bfc1b7`, radius `6px`.
- Sequence/dwell nodes can be pill/full-radius for compact process markers.
- No drop shadows.

## Node Types

Implement custom node types when needed:
- `FacilityNode` (storage, reactor, corridor, etc.)
- `MachineNode` (transport/actor)
- `StepNode` (sequence markers such as 1, 2, 3)
- `DwellNode` (small process/dwell indicators)

## Edges and Routing

- Use `smoothstep` edges (orthogonal look), not free curved spaghetti.
- Define explicit `Handle` positions (`Left/Right/Top/Bottom`) on custom nodes.
- For left-to-right flows, prefer Right -> Left handle connections.
- Edge color in muted hairline family (`#bfc1b7` / `#6c6e63`) with subtle arrowheads.
- Consider edge labels for step numbers to reduce node clutter.

## Layout Strategy

- Pick one primary direction (LR or TB) and keep it consistent.
- Snap positions to a visible grid (24px/48px increments).
- Keep generous spacing between major facilities (80px+).
- Group major phases in clear tiers/swimlanes when it improves readability.
- If auto-layout is used (`dagre`/`elkjs`), configure for strict directional flow.

## React Flow Setup Baseline

- Set React Flow background to `#eeefe9`.
- Use subtle dotted background (`#dcdfd2`) if a grid is needed.
- Keep controls flat: bordered, rounded, no shadows.

## Quality Checks

- Paths are readable at a glance; no node-edge overlaps.
- Diagram communicates chronology/physical flow without explanation.
- Visual style stays consistent with OptiFuel UI guidance.
